<div id="review_135588488" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/135588488" />
    <a title="Liz De Coster" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/258616-liz-de-coster"><img alt="Liz De Coster" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1437504879p2/258616.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/135588488?book_show_action=true">Dec 18, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Liz De Coster" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Liz De Coster" href="/user/show/258616-liz-de-coster">Liz De Coster</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/258616-liz-de-coster?shelf=food">food</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer135588488" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15468774763243467324">I was a bit disappointed in this book. I was anticipating a basic how-to of creating your own recipes based on the titular ratios, which was only loosely the focus of the book. While reading it, I felt that there were so many caveats and addendums to each ratio that it would be difficult to memorize and utilize the ratios in a home kitchen. The author was probably going for flexibility, but lost some authority in the process. I didn&apos;t get much from this book, either recipes or knowledge, that I </span>
  <span id="freeText15468774763243467324" style="display:none">I was a bit disappointed in this book. I was anticipating a basic how-to of creating your own recipes based on the titular ratios, which was only loosely the focus of the book. While reading it, I felt that there were so many caveats and addendums to each ratio that it would be difficult to memorize and utilize the ratios in a home kitchen. The author was probably going for flexibility, but lost some authority in the process. I didn't get much from this book, either recipes or knowledge, that I hadn't already gotten from other authors, such as <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/58480.Alton_Brown" title="Alton Brown" rel="nofollow noopener">Alton Brown</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/58484.Harold_McGee" title="Harold McGee" rel="nofollow noopener">Harold McGee</a> or <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/43684.Shirley_Corriher" title="Shirley Corriher" rel="nofollow noopener">Shirley Corriher</a>, and I think <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/138067.Sally_Schneider" title="Sally Schneider" rel="nofollow noopener">Sally Schneider</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/236008.The_Improvisational_Cook" title="The Improvisational Cook by Sally Schneider" rel="nofollow noopener">The Improvisational Cook</a> does a better job illustrating variations on a recipe theme than this book does. If, however, you haven't read any of these authors, Ruhlman is a fine (if visually bland) place to start.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15468774763243467324" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


