<div id="review_3910235898" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3910235898" />
    <a title="Xander" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/125412798-xander"><img alt="Xander" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3910235898?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Xander" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Xander" href="/user/show/125412798-xander">Xander</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3910235898" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11242310712675165946">Ratio is a wonderful book. Michael Ruhlman teaches the practical ratios in cooking that are the foundation of most recipes a cook will encounter. Ratio gives the reasons for why ingredients are proportioned the way they are, what functions they serve, and at the end of many of the chapters it gives a basic recipe using these ratios.<br/><br/>To say that Ratio is a cookbook wouldn&apos;t be quite right. It is a book about cooking, but the point of the book is to teach you how to make changes to or even create y</span>
  <span id="freeText11242310712675165946" style="display:none">Ratio is a wonderful book. Michael Ruhlman teaches the practical ratios in cooking that are the foundation of most recipes a cook will encounter. Ratio gives the reasons for why ingredients are proportioned the way they are, what functions they serve, and at the end of many of the chapters it gives a basic recipe using these ratios.<br /><br />To say that Ratio is a cookbook wouldn't be quite right. It is a book about cooking, but the point of the book is to teach you how to make changes to or even create your own recipes. If you understand the purpose of the ingredients and the ratios to use, you can know exactly what you can substitute in almost any situation. In addition to the chemical and mathematical nature of cooking, the book includes some tips that are simply good things to know.<br /><br />I would like to address a complaint I have seen about this book, that being that he uses advanced culinary terms that beginning cooks may not understand in his book, making it less accessable. I believe that with the contents of this book, fairly advanced technical terms are perfectly suitable, as I do not think this book should be your first dip into the culinary arts. That being said, it is perfect for bringing you to the next step of breaking away from the basics, and using new terms can give you more to look into and encourages you to learn more than what one could teach in a single book, making it great for cooks who know the very basics and want to take a deeper dive.<br /><br />I think Ratio is a great read and I would consider it a must-read for aspiring bakers.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11242310712675165946" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

